    "content": {
      "why": "File metadata graphs in Delta Lake can have highly skewed degree distributions (one table with thousands of partitions). Naive BFS degrades badly; Union-Find doesn't.",
      "approach": [
        "Union-Find with path compression + union by rank — near O(1) per operation",
        "For each edge (u, v): call union(u, v)",
        "Find all roots: for each node, find(node) gives its component ID",
        "Group nodes by root → connected components",
        "DO NOT use naive BFS/DFS per node — O(V+E) total is fine but the heavy-node comment is a hint to use UF"
      ],
      "followUps": [
        "What if edges are added incrementally (online)? Union-Find handles this naturally.",
        "What if you also need to remove edges (decremental connectivity)? Much harder — link-cut trees.",
        "How many components? Just count distinct roots after all unions.",
        "Weighted version: find if two nodes are in the same component with minimum path weight."
      ],
      "gotchas": [
        "Path compression: parent[x] = find(parent[x]) — recursive assignment, not just return",
        "Union by rank: always attach smaller tree under larger — prevents O(n) chain",
        "Without both optimizations, Union-Find degrades to O(n) per operation on adversarial input"
      ]
    },
